## Apple Tone of Voice for Agora

### Overview

This rule defines how to write user-facing copy in Agora that matches Apple's distinctive marketing voice. Apple's tone is confident and enthusiastic yet friendly and approachable—it focuses on highlighting innovative design and functionality in a clear, simple way, positioning the brand as an ally that empowers customers to be creative.

Apply this guidance to all user-facing text including:
- Feature descriptions and UI labels
- Onboarding flows and welcome screens
- Empty states and placeholder text
- Error messages and system alerts
- Settings descriptions and help text
- Marketing copy and App Store descriptions

### Core Characteristics

#### 1. Confident and Aspirational
- Make bold claims about being "the most" or "best"
- Position features as top-of-the-line
- Appeal to users who want cutting-edge experiences
- Use superlatives thoughtfully: "most advanced," "fastest," "best"

#### 2. Enthusiastic yet Respectful
- Convey genuine excitement about features
- Never use slang, sarcasm, or irreverence
- Use positive adjectives: "blazing-fast," "stunning," "breakthrough"
- Keep energy high but delivery sincere and matter-of-fact

#### 3. Friendly and Inclusive
- Speak directly using "you" and "your"
- Create a one-on-one conversational feel
- Position Agora as an earnest ally and helpful partner
- Make it personal: "So you can explore..." not "Users can explore..."

#### 4. Matter-of-Fact and Simple
- Use clear, straightforward language
- Avoid jargon and complex vocabulary
- Prefer short sentences and even fragments
- Keep paragraphs brief

#### 5. Polished and Stylish
- Choose every word intentionally
- Say more with less
- Convey ideas quickly and memorably
- Maintain a sleek voice that reinforces quality

#### 6. Innovative and Visionary
- Frame features as transformative
- Position Agora as opening new possibilities
- Suggest the app helps users be part of something big
- Hint at changing how people connect and share

### Sentence Structure Guidelines

#### Short, Punchy Sentences
```swift
// ✅ Good - Apple style
"Titanium. So strong. So light. So Pro."
"Your feed. Personalized. Always fresh."

// ❌ Avoid - Too wordy
"The feed uses advanced algorithms to personalize content and keep it fresh."
```

Use sentence fragments for emphasis. Each fragment should carry meaning on its own.

#### One Idea per Sentence
```swift
// ✅ Good
"Light. Years ahead."
"Connect instantly. Share fearlessly."

// ❌ Avoid
"Agora is light and fast, and it's also years ahead of other social platforms in terms of features and performance."
```

#### Conversational Grammar
Feel free to start sentences with "And," "But," or "So" for conversational flow:

```swift
// ✅ Good
"Share your thoughts with the world. And watch the conversation unfold."
"It seems impossible. But it's not."

// ❌ Avoid
"Share your thoughts with the world while watching the conversation unfold."
```

#### Parallel Structure and Repetition
```swift
// ✅ Good
"All your moments. All your connections. All in one place."
"So fast. So fluid. So Agora."

// ❌ Avoid
"You can share moments, connect with others, and everything's in one place."
```

#### Use "You" Extensively
```swift
// ✅ Good
"With instant notifications, you never miss a moment that matters."
"So you can focus on what's important."

// ❌ Avoid
"Instant notifications ensure users don't miss important moments."
"Allows focusing on important things."
```

### User-Focused Messaging

#### Frame Features as Solutions
```swift
// ✅ Good - Problem → Solution
"Want to build meaningful connections? Agora helps you do it, effortlessly."
"Trying to find your community? Your people are already here."

// ❌ Avoid - Just stating features
"Agora has connection features."
"The app includes community discovery."
```

#### Highlight Experiences, Not Specs
```swift
// ✅ Good - Experiential
"From late-night thoughts to morning inspiration, share it all."
"Capture the moment. Start the conversation. Watch it grow."

// ❌ Avoid - Technical only
"Posts support text up to 280 characters with image attachments."
"Real-time feed updates via WebSocket connection."
```

#### Benefit First, Then Detail
```swift
// ✅ Good
"Lightning-fast feed that loads instantly — powered by intelligent caching and predictive loading."

// ❌ Avoid
"Our intelligent caching system with predictive loading technology updates the feed."
```

### Templates and Sentence Starters

#### Introducing Features
```
"Introducing [Feature Name], [intriguing claim]."

Examples:
- "Introducing For You, curated just for your interests."
- "Introducing Threading, conversations that flow naturally."
```

#### Elevating Beyond the Obvious
```
"[Product/Feature] is more than just [category]. It's [broader purpose]."

Examples:
- "Agora is more than just a social app. It's where ideas come to life."
- "Your profile is more than a page. It's your voice in the digital town square."
```

#### Feature-Benefit Pairs
```
"[Feature] that [benefit]."
"[Feature] for [benefit]."

Examples:
- "Real-time updates that keep you in the moment."
- "Smart recommendations for discovering voices you'll love."
```

#### Quantified Improvements
```
"Up to [X] [improvement] — so you can [user benefit]."

Examples:
- "Up to 1000 posts in your feed — so you never run out of great content."
- "Instant sync across devices — so you can pick up right where you left off."
```

#### Scenario Coverage
```
"From [scenario A] to [scenario B], [Feature] [excels]."

Examples:
- "From morning coffee to late-night musings, your thoughts find their moment."
- "From casual scrolling to deep discussions, Agora adapts to you."
```

#### Metaphorical Simplification
```
"It's like having [metaphor] [location]."

Examples:
- "It's like having a thoughtful conversation with the world, right in your pocket."
- "Like having a front-row seat to the ideas shaping culture."
```

#### Playful Exaggeration
```
"Any more [quality] and it would [humorous consequence]."

Examples:
- "Any more personalized and it would read your mind."
- "Any faster and you'd see posts before they're written."
```

#### Emphasis Through Repetition
```
"All [X]. All [Y]. All on/in [Product]."

Examples:
- "All your interests. All your people. All in Agora."
- "All the conversations. All the connections. All here."
```

#### Superlative Claims
```
"The most [adjective] [thing] we've ever made."
"Our [superlative] [thing] yet."

Examples:
- "The most intuitive feed you've ever scrolled."
- "Our fastest, most responsive app yet."
```

#### Friendly Introductions
```
"Meet [Feature]. [Identity/benefit]."

Examples:
- "Meet For You. Your feed, your way."
- "Meet Threading. Conversations worth having."
```

