### Writing Checklist

Before finalizing any copy, verify:

- [ ] Uses "you" and "your" to speak directly to users
- [ ] Leads with benefits, not features
- [ ] Uses short, punchy sentences (mix with occasional longer ones)
- [ ] Feels confident but not arrogant
- [ ] Sounds enthusiastic but not over-the-top
- [ ] Includes at least one scenario or use case the user can relate to
- [ ] Avoids jargon and technical terms (or explains them simply)
- [ ] Could be read aloud naturally
- [ ] Feels like it's from a helpful ally, not a corporate entity
- [ ] Makes the user feel empowered or inspired

### Do's and Don'ts

#### ✅ Do
- Make bold, confident claims (if true)
- Use superlatives thoughtfully ("most," "best," "fastest")
- Start sentences with "And," "But," "So" for flow
- Use sentence fragments for emphasis
- Speak directly with "you"
- Paint pictures of use cases and scenarios
- Include subtle wordplay or metaphors
- Lead with benefits, follow with features
- Keep it simple and scannable

#### ❌ Don't
- Use slang, jargon, or overly technical language
- Be sarcastic, snarky, or irreverent
- Write long, complex sentences
- Use exclamation points excessively (one per screen max)
- Make claims you can't back up
- Focus only on technical specs
- Use corporate-speak or passive voice
- Overexplain—trust the user's intelligence
- Use humor that could fall flat or feel forced

